Total download size: 75 M
</pre>
<h4>Architecture</h4>
<p>If you&#8217;re serving more than 5 million hits a day, you&#8217;ll want to take a different approach than if you&#8217;re serving 500,000 hits a day.  For a small server, like mine, which can handle up to perhaps 1,000,000 hits a day, you&#8217;ll want everything running on the same box:</p>
<p><img id="image2278" src="http://elliottback.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2007/06/simple-server.png" alt="simple-server.png" /></p>
<p>For a more complicated server, you&#8217;ll split off the MYSQL component onto a hefty box, with Apache/PHP instances on a cluster of loadbalanced other boxes:</p>
<p><img id="image2277" src="http://elliottback.com/wp/wp-content/uploads/2007/06/complex-server.png" alt="complex-server.png" /></p>
<h4>Conclusion</h4>
<p>There&#8217;s no good reason for Wordpress or your site to be slow, except your own negligence.  Cache everything.  Monitor performance.  Use the latest versions of your software.  Configure it intelligently.  If you take an active part in every bit of software that powers your site, soon you&#8217;ll find things fit together more smoothly than before, and the secrets of a fast server will naturally fall into place.</p>
